{"parse":{"title":"flesh","pageid":6883,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|flesh}}, {{m|enm|flesch}}, {{m|enm|flæsch}}, from {{inh|en|ang|flǣsċ}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*flaiski}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*flaiski}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*pleh₁ḱ-|t=to tear, peel off}}.\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|yol|vleash}}, {{m|yol|vlesh|t=flesh}}, {{cog|frr|flaasch}}, {{m|frr|flaosk}}, {{m|frr|Fleesk}}, {{m|frr|fleäsk}}, {{m|frr|floask}}, {{m|frr|flääsk}}, {{m|frr|flååsch|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|stq|Flaask|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|fy|fleis|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|cim|blòas}}, {{m|cim|vlaisch}}, {{m|cim|vlòas|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|nl|vlees}}, {{m|nl|vleesch|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|de|Fleisch|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|nds-de,lb|Fleesch|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|wym|fłaś|t=meat; muscle}}, {{cog|yi|פֿלייש|t=flesh, meat}}, {{cog|da|flæsk|t=pork; bacon}}, {{cog|fo,is,nn|flesk|t=pork; bacon}}, {{cog|sv|fläsk|t=pork}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/flɛʃ/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-flesh.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛʃ|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|-|+}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q13119823}}The [[soft tissue]] of the [[body]], especially [[muscle]] and [[fat]].\n#* '''1918''', Fannie Farmer, ''[[s:Boston Cooking-School Cook Book/Chapter 17|Boston Cooking-School Cook Book]]'', Chapter XVII: Poultry and Game:\n#*: The '''flesh''' of chicken, fowl, and turkey has much shorter fibre than that of ruminating animals, and is not intermingled with fat,—the fat always being found in layers directly under the skin, and surrounding the intestines.\n# The skin of a human or animal.\n# {{lb|en|by extension}} [[bare|Bare]] [[arms]], [[bare]] [[legs]], bare torso.\n# [[animal|Animal]] tissue regarded as [[food]]; [[meat]] (but sometimes excluding [[fish]]).\n#: {{hypo|en|venison}}\n#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtDrthr|17.2|2|XV|ij|passage=Thenne syr launcelot sayd / fader what shalle I do / Now sayd the good man / I requyre yow take this hayre that was this holy mans and putte it nexte thy skynne / and it shalle preuaylle the gretely / syr and I wille doo hit sayd sir launcelot / Also I charge you that ye ete no '''flesshe''' as longe as ye be in the quest of the sancgreal / nor ye shalle drynke noo wyne / and that ye here masse dayly and ye may doo hit}}\n<!--Prior quotr#*:I charge the that thou ete no '''fleysshe''' as longe as ye be in the Queste of Sankgreall, nother ye shall drynke no wyne-->\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale Pentateuch|Leviticus|7|19–21|XI|verso=1|The '''fleſh''' that twycheth any vnclene thinge ſhall not be eaten. but burnt with fire: and all that be clene in their fleſh, maye eate '''fleſh'''. Yf any ſoule eate of the '''fleſh''' of the peaceofferynges, that pertayne vnto the Lorde and hys vnclenneſſe yet apon him, the ſame ſoule ſhall periſſhe from amonge his peoole.{{sic}} Moreouer yf a ſoule twych any vnclene thinge, whether it be the vnclenneſſe of man or of any vnclene beeſt or any abhominacion that is vnclene: ãd thẽ eate of the '''fleſh''' of the peaceoffrynges whiche pertayne vnto the Lord, that ſoule ſhall periſſh from his people.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=8 May 2018|author=Raj Patel; Jason W Moore|title=How the chicken nugget became the true symbol of our era|titleurl=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/may/08/how-the-chicken-nugget-became-the-true-symbol-of-our-era|journal=The Guardian\n|passage=Chicken is already the most popular meat in the US, and is projected to be the planet’s favourite '''flesh''' by 2020.}}\n# The [[human]] body as a physical entity.\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale Pentateuch|Leviticus|6|10|IX|And the preaſt ſhall put on his lynen albe and his lynen breches apon his '''fleſh''', and take awaye the aſſhes whiche the fire of the burntſacrifice in the altare hath made, and put them beſyde the alter, {{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=15 Feb 86|volume=13|number=31|journal=Gay Community News|page=7|title=Carl Wittman: An Activist's Life|author=Michael Bronski|text=In my political/cultural mythology Carl remained this larger-than-life figure {{...}} But knowing Carl, the fantasy made '''flesh''', was a different experience. The keen mind that wrote \"A Gay Manifesto\" was  even more perceptive and challenging in real life.}}\n# {{lb|en|religion}} The [[mortal]] body of a human being, contrasted with the [[spirit]] or [[soul]].\n#* {{RQ:KJV|1 Peter|1|24|passage=For all '''flesh''' is as grasse, and all the glory of man as the flowre of grasse: the grasse withereth, and the flowre thereof falleth away.}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Galatians|5|17|passage=For the '''flesh''' lusteth against the Spirit, and the spirit against the '''flesh''': and these are contrary the one to the other: so that yee cannot doe the things that yee would.}}\n#* '''1929''' January, Bassett Morgan ([[s:Author:Grace Jones|Grace Jones]]), ''[[s:Avon Fantasy Reader/Issue 10/Bimini|Bimini]]'', first published in ''{{w|Weird Tales}}'', reprinted 1949, in ''[[s:Avon Fantasy Reader/Issue 10|Avon Fantasy Reader, Issue 10]]'',\n#*: But death had no gift for me, no power to free me from '''flesh'''.\n# {{lb|en|religion}} The [[evil]] and corrupting principle working in man.\n# The soft, often edible, parts of [[fruit]]s or [[vegetable]]s.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=Diana Beresford-Kroeger|title=Arboretum America: A Philosophy of the Forest|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=7HgjzLERa1kC&pg=PA80&dq=flesh+walnut&hl=en&ei=45EyTpb4A4_qmAX9k73wCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=flesh%20walnut&f=false|page=81\n|passage=The '''flesh''' of black walnuts was a protein-packed winter food carefully hoarded in tall, stilted buildings.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Tenderness of feeling; gentleness.\n#* {{RQ:Cowper Task|passage=There is no '''flesh''' in man's obdurate heart.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Kindred; stock; race.\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Genesis|37|27|passage=He is our brother and our '''flesh'''.}}\n# A [[yellow]]ish [[pink]] [[color]]; the color of some [[Caucasian]] human skin.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|author=w:Tayari Jones|title=w:An American Marriage|publisher=Oneworld Publications|page=243|passage=She opened [...] a third that was the peachy white that crayon companies used to call “'''flesh'''”.}}\n#: {{color panel|FFC090}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* See also [[Thesaurus:body]]\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|body tissue}}\n* Akan: {{t|ak|ɛnam}}, {{t|ak|nam}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|mish|m}}, {{t+|sq|tul|m}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|لَحْم|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|لحم|m|tr=laḥm}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|միս}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|мяса|n}}, {{t+|be|це́ла|n}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{t|bcl|unod}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|месо́|n}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|carn|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|肉|tr=ròu}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|maso|n}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|kød|n}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|vlees|n}}\n* Egyptian: {{t-egy|jwf|h=i-W:f-F51:Z2ss}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|karno}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|liha}}\n* Faroese: {{t+|fo|kjøt|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|liha}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|chair}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Fleisch|n}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐌼𐌰𐌼𐌼𐍉|f}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|σάρκα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|σάρξ|f}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|ʻiʻo}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|בָּשָׂר|m|tr=basár}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|क्रव्य|m}}, {{t+|hi|मांस|m}}\n* Hmong:\n*: White Hmong: {{t|mww|nqaij}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|hús}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|hold|n}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|karno}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|daging}}\n* Iranun: {{t|ill|sapu'}}\n* Irish: {{t+|ga|feoil|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|carne|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|肉|tr=にく, niku}}, {{t+|ja|身|tr=み, mi}}\n* Kaurna: {{t|zku|itya}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|សាច់}}, {{t+|km|មំសៈ}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|살}}, {{t+|ko|고기}}\n* Lao: {{t+|lo|ຊີ້ນ}}, {{t|lo|ມັງສະ}}\n* Latgalian: {{t|ltg|mīsa|f}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|miesa|f}}, {{t+|lv|ķermenis|m}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t+|lt|kūnas}}\n* Low German: {{t|nds|Fleesch|n}}\n* Lutuv: {{t|clt|saa}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+|mk|месо|n}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|മാംസം}}\n* Manchu: {{t|mnc|ᠶᠠᠯᡳ}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kiko}}, {{t|mi|uaua}}, {{t|mi|tōrōpuku}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|atsįʼ}}\n* Odia: {{t+|or|ମାଂସ}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|گوشت|tr=gušt}}\n* Piedmontese: {{t|pms|carn|f}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{t|pdt|Fleesch|n}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|ciało|n}}, {{t+|pl|mięso|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|carne|f}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|carne|f}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|мягкая [[ткань]]|f}}, {{t+|ru|плоть|f}} {{qualifier|poetic}}, {{t+|ru|мясо|n}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|ru|те́ло|m}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|क्रव्य|n}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|feòil|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|meso|n}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|carne|f}}\n* Sranan Tongo: {{t|srn|meti}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|chembechembe}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|kött|n}}\n* Tajik: {{t+|tg|гӯшт}}\n* Tarifit: {{t|rif|aysum|m}}, {{t|rif|aksum|m}}\n* Telugu: {{t+|te|కండ}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|เนื้อ}}\n* Tibetan: {{t|bo|ཤ་}}\n* Tigrinya: {{t+|ti|ስጋ}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{t|tpi|mit}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|et}}\n* Udmurt: {{t|udm|сӥль}}\n* Ugaritic: {{t|uga|𐎌𐎛𐎗}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|м'я́со|n}}, {{t|uk|плоть|f}}, {{t|uk|ті́ло|n}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|مانس|m|tr=mā̃s}}, {{t|ur|گوشت|m|tr=gośt}}, {{t|ur|لحم|m|tr=laham}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|ئەت}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|et}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|mid}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|tchå|f}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|cnawd}}\n* Yurok: {{t|yur|tewon}}\n* Zulu: {{t+|zu|inyama|c9|c10}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|skin}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|кожа|f}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|hud}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|vel|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|iho}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|peau}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|pel|m}}, {{t|gl|pelexo|m}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Haut|n}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|δέρμα|n}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|χρώς|m}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|त्वचा|f}}, {{t+|hi|चमड़ा|m}}, {{t+|hi|चमड़ी|f}}, {{t+|hi|खाल|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|bőr}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pele|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ко́жа|f}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|craiceann|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pellejo|m}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|ngozi}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{t|tpi|skin}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|deri}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|جلد|f|tr=jild}}, {{t|ur|پوست|m|tr=post}}, {{t|ur|کھال|f|tr=khāl}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|skin}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|animal tissue as food}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|لَحْمٌ|m}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|միս}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|месо|n}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|carn|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|肉|tr=bah}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|kød|n}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|vlees|n}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|liha}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|liha}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|chair|f}}, {{t+|fr|viande|f}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Fleisch|n}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κρέας|n}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|κρέας|n}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|मांस|m}}, {{t+|hi|लहम|m}}, {{t+|hi|गोश्त|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|hús}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|daging}}\n* Irish: {{t+|ga|feoil|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|肉|tr=にく, niku}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|gaļa|f}}\n* Low German: {{t|nds|Fleesch|n}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|മാംസം}}, {{t+|ml|ഇറച്ചി}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kiko}}\n* Pashto: {{t+|ps|غوښه|f|tr=γwəxa}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{t|pdt|Fleesch|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|carne|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|мя́со|n}}, {{t+|ru|плоть|f}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|feòil|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|meso|n}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|carne|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|kinofu}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|kött|n}}\n* Tarifit: {{t|rif|aysum|m}}, {{t|rif|aksum|m}}\n* Tigrinya: {{t+|ti|ስጋ}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{t|tpi|mit}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|et}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|گوشت|m|tr=gośt}}, {{t|ur|لحم|m|tr=laham}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|ئەت}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|et}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|tchå|f}}\n* Zulu: {{t+|zu|inyama|c9|c10}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|human body entity}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|մարմին}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|це́ла|n}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|тяло|n}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|tělo|n}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|krop}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|corps}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|corpo|m}}, {{t+|gl|carne|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Fleisch|n}}, {{t+|de|Leib|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|σάρκα|f}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|korpo}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|colainn|f}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t+|lv|ķermenis|m}}\n* Mpade: {{t|mpi|shu}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|ciało|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|corpo|m}}, {{t+|pt|carne|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|те́ло|n}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|feòil|f}}, {{t|gd|craiceann|m}}\n* Slovak: {{t+|sk|telo|n}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|meso|n}}, {{t+|sl|telọ̑|n}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|carne|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|ngozi}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{t|tpi|mit}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|ті́ло|n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|(religion) mortal body}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|тлен|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|liha}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|chair|f}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne|f}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{t|ht|lachè}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|देह|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|test}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|meso|n}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|เนื้อหนัง}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|(religion) evil, sin, corruption}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|liha}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|chair|f}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne|f}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{t|ht|lachè}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|colainn|f}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|edible part of fruit/vegetable}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|dužina|f}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|kød}}, {{t|da|frugtkød}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|vruchtvlees|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|malto}}, {{t+|fi|hedelmäliha}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pulpe}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne|f}}, {{t+|gl|polpa|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Fleisch|n}}, {{t+|de|Fruchtfleisch|n}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|σάρκα|f}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|गुद्दा|m}}, {{t+|hi|गूदा|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|hús}}, {{t+|hu|gyümölcshús}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|pulpo}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|果肉|tr=kaniku}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|carō|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|mīkstums|m}}\n* Māori: {{t+|mi|kākano}} {{qualifier|of coconuts}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|miąższ|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|polpa|f}}, {{t+|pt|carne|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|мя́коть|f}}\n* Samoan: {{t|sm|ʻaʻano}} {{qualifier|of coconuts}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|feòil|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|carne|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|ngozi}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|fruktkött|n}}\n* Telugu: {{t+|te|గుజ్జు}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|et}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|ئەت}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|et}}\n* Volapük: {{t|vo|flukapulp}}, {{t|vo|pulp}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|colour}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|телесен}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|carn|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|肉色|tr=juk6 sik1}}\n*: Hakka: {{t|hak|肉色|tr=ngiuk-set}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|肉色|tr=bah-sek}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|肉色|tr=ròusè}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|kødfarve}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|mensenkleur|f}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|carnation|f}}, {{t+|fr|chair|f}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|carne}}\n* German: {{t|de|Fleischfarbe|f}}\n* Indonesian: {{t|id|merah daging}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|肌色|tr=hadairo}}, {{t+|ja|ペールオレンジ|tr=pēru orenji}}, {{t|ja|うすだいだい|tr=usudaidai}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|살색}}, {{t+|ko|살구색}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|hudfarge}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|cielisty|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|bege}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|телесный}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|carne|f}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|тілесний}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Persian: {{t+check|fa|گوشت}} (gusht) (1), {{t+check|fa|پوست}} (pust) (2,4,5)\n* Woiwurrung: {{t|wyi|weeringam}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[reward]] (a hound, bird of prey etc.) with flesh of the animal killed, to excite it for further hunting; to [[train]] (an animal) to have an [[appetite]] for flesh.\n#* {{RQ:Smollett Peregrine Pickle|volume=I|8|text=Before they had '''fleshed''' the hounds, however, he recollected himself {{...}}.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[bury]] (something, especially a weapon) in flesh.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1933|author=Robert E. Howard|title=The Scarlet Citadel|passage=Give me a clean sword and a clean foe to '''flesh''' it in.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[inure]] or [[habituate]] someone {{m|en|in}} or {{m|en|to}} a given practice. {{defdate|16th|18th c.}}\n#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=7|book=II|passage=And whosoever could now joyne us together, and eagerly '''flesh''' all our people to a common enterprise, we should make our ancient military name and chivalrous credit to flourish againe.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[glut]].\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To put flesh on; to [[fatten]].\n# To remove the flesh from the skin during the making of [[leather]].\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|to put flesh on}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|угоявам}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|opfede}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|vervetten}}, {{t+|nl|verdikken}}, {{t+|nl|aandikken}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ხორცშესხმა}}\n* German: {{t+|de|zunehmen}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|پرواربندی}} (parvaarbandi)\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|engordar}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|ngozi}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|To add details}}\n* German: {{t+|de|ausarbeiten}}, {{t+|de|untermauern}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|enfeitar}}\n* Swahili: {{t|sw|jazia}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to remove the flesh}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|одирам}}\n* German: {{t+|de|entfleischen}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|descarnar}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|descarnar}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|bambua}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|کھال اتارنا|tr=khāl utārnā}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Derived terms===\n{{col4|en|title=Terms derived from the noun or verb ''flesh''|flesh-pressing\n|arm of flesh|flesh-bag\n|become one flesh\n|cockflesh|cowflesh|dead flesh\n|dickflesh\n|sharkflesh\n|exchange flesh\n|flesh and blood|flesh and bone|flesh and bones\n|flesh broth|flesh brush\n|flesh-colored|flesh-crawling\n|flesher |flesh-eating |flesh-eating disease\n|flesh fly\n|flesh glue|breastflesh|calfflesh|deerflesh|deflesh|disflesh|enflesh|fleshbag|fleshen|fleshfest|fleshfly|fleshhood|fleshhook|fleshie|fleshify|fleshless|fleshlight|fleshlike|fleshling|fleshloaf|fleshly|fleshmeat|fleshmeet|fleshment|fleshmonger|fleshquake|fleshworm|fruitflesh|goatflesh|horseflesh|inflesh|oxflesh|sheepflesh|unflesh|womanflesh|woodflesh\n|fleshhouse\n|fleshing\n|flesh loaf\n|flesh out|flesh one's maiden sword|flesh on the bones\n|fleshpot\n|flesh side\n|flesh tunnel\n|flesh-wing|flesh wound\n|fleshy\n|goose flesh|go the way of all flesh\n|human flesh search engine|human-flesh search\n|in the flesh\n|make fish of one and flesh of another|make someone's flesh creep|make someone's flesh crawl\n|neither fish nor flesh\n|one flesh\n|pound of flesh|press the flesh|proud flesh|pleasures of the flesh|press flesh\n|sack of flesh|swine flesh|swine-flesh|swineflesh\n|the spirit is willing but the flesh is weak|thorn in the flesh\n|way of all flesh|what's bred in the bone will come out in the flesh\n}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|carrion}}\n* {{l|en|incarnate}}\n* {{l|en|sarcoid}}\n* [[Appendix:Colors]]\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=efhls|Fehls|shelf}}\n\n{{C|en|Hides|Oranges}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|enm|flech|fleesh|fleisch|fleische|fleish|flesch|flesche|fless|flessh}}\n* {{alter|enm|flæsc|flæsch|flæsh||early}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|enm|ang|flǣsċ}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*flaiski}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*flaiski}}, from {{der|enm|ine-pro|*pleh₁ḱ-||to tear, peel off}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|enm|/flɛːʃ/|/flɛʃ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{enm-noun|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|flesh}} {{gloss|especially that of a mammal}}\n# {{lb|enm|Christianity|theology}} A [[communion wafer]]\n# {{lb|enm|anatomy}} A [[muscle]]\n# [[meat]], {{l|en|flesh}} for consumption\n# A [[human]] or [[being]]\n# The [[body]], [[physical]] [[existence]], [[nature]] {{gloss|especially that of a human}}\n# [[sexual intercourse]], [[copulation]]\n\n====Usage notes====\nMuch like with {{noncog|en|fish}}, this word is a collective noun, but can be pluralised to refer to different meats.\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|en|flesh}}\n* {{desc|sco|flesch}}\n* {{desc|yol|vleash|alts=1}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=flē̆sh |pos=n |id=MED16282 |accessdate=2018-04-08}}\n\n{{C|enm|Meats|Sex}}"}}